---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Raise & Resolve CIBIL Dispute | Correction Process | TrueCred Loan Expert">

<!-- Page Hero -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <a href="/pages/credit-score">Credit Score</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span>Raise & Resolve CIBIL Dispute</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Raise & Resolve <span class="gradient-text">CIBIL Dispute</span></h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Found errors in your CIBIL report? Learn how to file a dispute, get incorrect information corrected, and protect your credit score from inaccurate data.</p>
      <div class="hero-highlights">
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-file-pen"></i>
          <span>Filing: Free of Cost</span>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-hourglass-half"></i>
          <span>Resolution: 30 Days</span>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-arrow-trend-up"></i>
          <span>Score Impact: +50 to +200</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page Content -->
  <section class="page-content">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="content-grid">

        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="content-main">

          <!-- Overview -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Overview</span>
              <h2>What is a CIBIL Dispute?</h2>
            </div>
            <p>A CIBIL dispute is a formal request you file with TransUnion CIBIL to correct inaccurate, outdated, or erroneous information in your credit report. Studies show that nearly 1 in 5 credit reports in India contain some form of error — from wrong account details to falsely reported late payments or accounts that don't belong to you.</p>
            <p>These errors can unfairly drag your CIBIL score down by 50 to 200+ points, leading to loan rejections, higher interest rates, or lower credit limits. Filing a dispute is your legal right under the Credit Information Companies (Regulation) Act, 2005, and CIBIL is required to investigate and resolve your dispute within 30 days.</p>
            <p>The dispute process is completely free and can be done online through the CIBIL website or through TrueCred's guided dispute assistance. Once an error is verified and corrected, your CIBIL score is automatically recalculated to reflect the accurate information.</p>
          </div>

          <!-- Common Errors Table -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Common Errors</span>
              <h2>Types of Errors You Can Dispute</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Here are the most common types of errors found in CIBIL reports and their potential impact on your score.</p>
            <table class="rate-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Error Type</th>
                  <th>Example</th>
                  <th>Score Impact</th>
                  <th>Resolution Time</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Wrong Personal Info</strong></td>
                  <td>Incorrect name, address, or DOB</td>
                  <td>Indirect (may cause mix-ups)</td>
                  <td>15–20 days</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>False Late Payment</strong></td>
                  <td>Payment marked late when paid on time</td>
                  <td><span style="color: #ef4444; font-weight: 600;">-50 to -100 points</span></td>
                  <td>20–30 days</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Account Not Yours</strong></td>
                  <td>Loan/card you never applied for</td>
                  <td><span style="color: #ef4444; font-weight: 600;">-100 to -200 points</span></td>
                  <td>30–45 days</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Wrong Balance/Limit</strong></td>
                  <td>Outstanding amount shown incorrectly</td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f97316; font-weight: 600;">-30 to -80 points</span></td>
                  <td>15–30 days</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Closed Account Shown Open</strong></td>
                  <td>Paid-off loan still shown as active</td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f59e0b; font-weight: 600;">-20 to -50 points</span></td>
                  <td>15–30 days</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Duplicate Account Entry</strong></td>
                  <td>Same loan appearing multiple times</td>
                  <td><span style="color: #f97316; font-weight: 600;">-40 to -100 points</span></td>
                  <td>20–30 days</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <!-- Dispute Process -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Process</span>
              <h2>How to File a CIBIL Dispute</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Filing a dispute involves identifying the error, gathering supporting documents, and submitting your case through the proper channels. Here's what you need to know about each method.</p>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Online via CIBIL Website (Recommended)</strong>
                  <p>Log in to your CIBIL account at cibil.com, navigate to "Dispute Centre," select the erroneous entry, describe the error, upload supporting documents, and submit. You'll receive a Dispute ID for tracking.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Through Your Lender (Parallel Approach)</strong>
                  <p>Contact the bank or NBFC that reported the incorrect data. They can submit a correction to CIBIL directly. This works well for wrong payment statuses or account closure issues since lenders are the data source.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Via Email to CIBIL</strong>
                  <p>Send a detailed dispute letter to info@cibil.com with your CIBIL report, specific errors highlighted, supporting documents, and PAN copy for identity verification. Keep the email professional and factual.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Documents You'll Need</strong>
                  <p>Bank statements proving on-time payments, loan closure/NOC certificates, payment receipts, account statements, PAN card copy, and any written communication with the lender regarding the dispute.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>What Happens After Filing</strong>
                  <p>CIBIL forwards your dispute to the concerned lender, who has 30 days to verify and respond. If the lender confirms the error, CIBIL corrects the report. If the lender doesn't respond within 30 days, CIBIL may remove the disputed information.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Escalation If Unresolved</strong>
                  <p>If your dispute isn't resolved satisfactorily, you can escalate to the RBI's Banking Ombudsman or file a complaint with the Consumer Forum. CIBIL is legally bound to investigate and correct verified errors.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Steps -->
          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Step by Step</span>
              <h2>CIBIL Dispute Resolution Process</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Follow this step-by-step guide to file and resolve your CIBIL dispute successfully.</p>
            <div class="steps-grid">
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <h3>Get Your Full CIBIL Report</h3>
                <p>Download your complete CIBIL report from TrueCred or cibil.com. Review every section — personal information, account details, payment history, and inquiry records — to identify all errors.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <h3>Gather Supporting Evidence</h3>
                <p>Collect documents that prove the error: bank statements, payment confirmations, loan closure certificates, NOC letters, or communication records with the lender. Clear evidence speeds up resolution.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <h3>File the Dispute Online</h3>
                <p>Log into the CIBIL Dispute Centre, select each incorrect item, describe the error clearly, upload your supporting documents, and submit. Note down the Dispute ID for each submission.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="step-card">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <h3>Track & Follow Up</h3>
                <p>Monitor your dispute status online using the Dispute ID. If no update within 15 days, follow up with both CIBIL and the concerned lender. Once resolved, check your updated CIBIL report to verify corrections.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="content-sidebar">

          <!-- Check Score Form -->
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-magnifying-glass"></i> Check Report for Errors</h3>
            <form class="sidebar-form" onsubmit="return false;">
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="Full Name" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="PAN Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="tel" class="form-input" placeholder="Mobile Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="date" class="form-input" placeholder="Date of Birth" required>
              </div>
              <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary btn-block" style="width:100%;justify-content:center;">
                Get CIBIL Report <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
              </button>
              <p class="form-disclaimer">
                <i class="fas fa-lock"></i> 100% safe & secure. No impact on your score.
              </p>
            </form>
          </div>

          <!-- Quick Links -->
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-link"></i> Quick Links</h3>
            <ul class="sidebar-links">
              <li><a href="/pages/credit-score"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Free Credit Score</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/cibil-score-pan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> CIBIL Check by PAN</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/increase-cibil-score"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Increase CIBIL Score</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/cibil-score-personal-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> CIBIL for Personal Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/cibil-score-credit-card"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> CIBIL for Credit Card</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/personal-loan"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Personal Loan</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/credit-cards"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> Credit Cards</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pages/calculators"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i> EMI Calculators</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About CIBIL Disputes</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>How long does it take to resolve a CIBIL dispute?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>CIBIL is mandated to resolve disputes within 30 days of filing. In practice, simple disputes (like wrong personal information) may be resolved in 15–20 days, while complex disputes involving account ownership or payment history corrections can take the full 30 days. If the lender doesn't respond within the timeframe, CIBIL may remove or correct the disputed data by default.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Is there a fee for filing a CIBIL dispute?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>No, filing a dispute with CIBIL is completely free of charge. You can raise as many disputes as needed at no cost. There is no limit on the number of disputes you can file, and you can dispute multiple items simultaneously. However, ensure your disputes are genuine and supported by evidence — frivolous or repeated disputes for the same resolved issue may delay processing.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>What if CIBIL rejects my dispute?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>If CIBIL rejects your dispute (usually because the lender verified the data as correct), you have several options: gather additional evidence and re-file the dispute; contact the lender directly with your documentation and request them to update the data; file a complaint with the RBI Banking Ombudsman; or approach the Consumer Disputes Redressal Forum. You can also add a 100-word personal statement to your CIBIL report explaining the disputed entry.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Can I dispute an account that belongs to someone with a similar name?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Yes, this is called a "mixed file" error and is more common than you'd think. If your CIBIL report shows accounts belonging to another person with a similar name, file a dispute immediately specifying that the account doesn't belong to you. Provide your PAN card, Aadhaar card, and any other identity proof. CIBIL will verify with the lender and remove the mismatched account, which can significantly boost your score.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>How much can my CIBIL score increase after a successful dispute?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>The score increase depends on the type and severity of the error corrected. Removing a false late payment mark can boost your score by 50–100 points. Removing a fraudulent account or incorrect default/write-off can increase it by 100–200+ points. Correcting a wrong outstanding balance that was inflating your utilisation ratio can add 30–80 points. The impact is greater if the error was recent and on a significant account.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page CTA -->
  <section class="page-cta">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Check Your CIBIL Report for Errors Now</h2>
      <p>Get your free CIBIL report, identify errors, and file disputes to reclaim the credit score you deserve. Don't let inaccurate data hold you back.</p>
      <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">
        Get Free Report <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Footer -->

</BaseLayout>
